They visited Morne Fortune, a National Trust site with monuments to St Lucian Nobel Laureates, Sir W Arthur Lewis and Sir Derek Walcott. Edward and Sophie, 57, wearing a polka dot dress for the visit, had faced protests earlier in the tour, with banners calling for an "end to colonialism" and "Britain your debt is outstanding." Prince Edward, 58, gave a reading yesterday during a lengthy service at the Holy Trinity Anglican Church, held to mark the Queen's Platinum Jubilee. The Wessexes are due to travel today to Antigua and Barbuda, where one organisation has already warned the couple to avoid "phoney sanctimony" over slavery. 